,"type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Dieter, Hans, Otto.","German and Jewish (Ashkenazic): habitational name from any of the places in Hesse and Saarland called Homburg, from the weak dative case (originally used after a preposition and article) of Old High German <i>hōh</i> ‘high’ + <i>burg</i> ‘fortress, fortified town’."],"variants":[{"name":"Homberg","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Otto, Fritz.  Jewish Aron.","German and Jewish (Ashkenazic):","habitational name from any of various places in Germany so called. The placename is derived from an inflected form of Old High German <i>hōh</i> ‘high’ + <i>berg</i> ‘mountain, hill’."]},{"name":"Humburg","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Katharina, Kurt.","Perhaps an altered form of German   Homburg  ."]}]},{"name":"Gertrude","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From a Germanic female personal name, derived from <i>gār</i>, <i>gēr</i> ‘spear’ + <i>þrūþ</i> ‘strength’. The name is not found in England immediately after the Conquest, but only in the later Middle English period. It may have been introduced by migrants from the Low Countries who came to England in connection with the cloth trade, and was certainly in consistent use in some areas throughout the 16th and 17th centuries, although it was not generally popular until the 19th century, when many medieval names were revived. It has now fallen from favour again."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Gertrude von Comburg was born before 1101, in Germany as the daughter of Heinrich Graf von Rothenburg and Gepa of Mergentheim. She married Konrad III. von Hohenstaufen Deutscher König about 1114. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. She died before 1131, in her hometown."},"et":{"before 1101–before 1131":"enne 1101–enne 1131","1101–1131":"1